1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,500
Imagine looking at the Roman Empire, like the very day before it fell, and then you look at Silicon Valley today, and you realize that mathematically, and I mean down to the exact geometric equation, they are making the exact same fatal mistake.

2
00:00:16,720 --> 00:00:18,080
It's a pretty wild thought.

3
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:31,100
It's mind-bending, because normally we treat these things as completely different chapters of history, right? I mean, you have the rise of humanity, the violent collapse of an empire, and now the looming shadow of artificial superintelligence.

4
00:00:31,200 --> 00:00:33,020
Yeah, completely different fields of study.

5
00:00:33,180 --> 00:00:40,300
Exactly. We have biology for our origins, history for our empires, and computer science for our future.

6
00:00:40,300 --> 00:00:50,700
Well, it's comforting to categorize the world like that. You know, we like our domains siloed, each with its own specific experts and its own safe, isolated narrative.

7
00:00:50,880 --> 00:00:51,100
Right.

8
00:00:51,540 --> 00:00:55,900
But the problem with complex systems is that they just don't respect our academic boundaries.

9
00:00:56,160 --> 00:01:03,640
No, they really don't. And when you step into the world of complex systems and mathematical geometry, those silos just completely dissolve.

10
00:01:03,800 --> 00:01:04,780
They absolutely do.

11
00:01:04,780 --> 00:01:12,720
Which brings us to our mission for today, because we're looking at a predictor landscape today that is honestly, well, it's staggering.

12
00:01:13,500 --> 00:01:26,920
What if you could predict the rise of human cooperation, the internal rot of a superpower, and the ultimate existential threat of a rogue AI, all using the exact same underlying mathematical architecture?

13
00:01:27,420 --> 00:01:29,840
It fundamentally changes how you perceive risk.

14
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:33,900
I mean, we're talking about a paradigm shift in how we analyze reality itself.

15
00:01:34,100 --> 00:01:39,120
The underlying structure governing all these seemingly disconnected events is actually identical.

16
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:44,820
Okay, let's unpack this, because we are jumping into a highly dense, absolutely fascinating deep dive today.

17
00:01:44,900 --> 00:01:47,940
We're looking at an independent research paper by an author named Fliction.

18
00:01:48,320 --> 00:01:50,840
It's titled Civilizations as Reachability Systems.

19
00:01:51,480 --> 00:01:52,560
And it's incredibly ambitious.

20
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:55,840
It is. It takes three major, completely distinct books.

21
00:01:55,940 --> 00:02:01,300
So that's Peter Turchin's Ultra Society, his follow-up Ages of Discord, and Darren McKee's Uncontrollable.

22
00:02:01,500 --> 00:02:04,940
And it unites them into one master mathematical theory.

23
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:18,300
Right. And just to give that some context for everyone, Turchin's Ultra Society is conventionally read as this deep dive into how large-scale human cooperation evolved over the last 10,000 years.

24
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:20,100
Right. Pre-history into history.

25
00:02:20,100 --> 00:02:26,920
Exactly. And then his next book, Ages of Discord, analyzes why complex societies collapse internally.

26
00:02:27,500 --> 00:02:31,080
So the cyclical destabilization that brings down empires.

27
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:32,500
The fall of Rome kind of stuff.

28
00:02:32,600 --> 00:02:33,240
Yeah, exactly.

29
00:02:33,740 --> 00:02:40,600
And then McKee's Uncontrollable is a contemporary text that's entirely focused on the alignment problem of artificial superintelligence.

30
00:02:40,940 --> 00:02:44,700
So we're spanning prehistory, recorded history, and the immediate future.

31
00:02:44,900 --> 00:02:45,640
All in one paper.

32
00:02:45,860 --> 00:02:46,100
Right.

33
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:56,000
So to you, listening right now, putting human evolution, the fall of Rome, and rogue AI into the same mathematical equation might sound, I don't know, like pure science fiction.

34
00:02:56,080 --> 00:02:57,140
This does sound like sci-fi.

35
00:02:57,280 --> 00:03:01,540
But we are going to look at history today, not through dates or battles or great leaders.

36
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:06,000
We are looking through something the paper calls admissible future manifolds.

37
00:03:06,400 --> 00:03:07,420
Which is a heavy term.

38
00:03:07,420 --> 00:03:08,220
It is.

39
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:13,880
But the central question we have to wrestle with today is actually quite simple, even if the math is complex.

40
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:14,560
Right.

41
00:03:14,720 --> 00:03:22,780
And that question is, what expands, contracts, or irreversibly closes the space of futures available to a civilization?

42
00:03:23,080 --> 00:03:24,360
I love how you phrase that.

43
00:03:24,360 --> 00:03:31,620
Well, by the end of this deep dive, the goal is to equip you with a completely new framework for analyzing the world around you.

44
00:03:32,180 --> 00:03:37,380
Whether that's global geopolitics or, honestly, just the trajectory of your own career.

45
00:03:37,580 --> 00:03:38,060
Yeah.

46
00:03:38,440 --> 00:03:42,160
We are mapping the invisible architecture of what is actually possible.

47
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:44,320
The invisible architecture of the possible.

48
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:46,340
That is, that's a great way to put it.

49
00:03:46,660 --> 00:03:50,260
But to start building this framework, we have to lay down some foundational geometry.

50
00:03:50,260 --> 00:03:57,960
I promise we wouldn't drown anyone in jargon, but we absolutely need to define a couple of core concepts to get off the ground.

51
00:03:58,120 --> 00:03:58,500
We do.

52
00:03:58,620 --> 00:04:01,360
Starting with something the paper calls state space.

53
00:04:01,660 --> 00:04:01,920
Right.

54
00:04:02,020 --> 00:04:04,220
So think of state space not as physical space.

55
00:04:04,300 --> 00:04:06,360
We aren't talking about galaxies or solar systems here.

56
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:07,040
No spaceships.

57
00:04:07,380 --> 00:04:08,180
No spaceships.

58
00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:11,260
Think of it as an abstract mathematical arena.

59
00:04:11,960 --> 00:04:17,740
In this arena, every single point represents a possible configuration of a civilization.

60
00:04:17,740 --> 00:04:20,080
Okay, give me a tangible example of that.

61
00:04:20,260 --> 00:04:22,240
How do I visualize a configuration?

62
00:04:22,660 --> 00:04:23,880
Let's use a chess board first.

63
00:04:24,600 --> 00:04:29,760
The state space of a chess game is every legally possible arrangement of pieces on that board.

64
00:04:29,840 --> 00:04:30,620
Oh, okay.

65
00:04:30,780 --> 00:04:32,500
So millions of possibilities.

66
00:04:32,620 --> 00:04:32,920
Exactly.

67
00:04:33,100 --> 00:04:35,340
Millions of points in that state space.

68
00:04:35,680 --> 00:04:37,700
Now, scale that up to a society.

69
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:38,260
Right.

70
00:04:38,360 --> 00:04:43,060
If your society has, say, a certain population size, a specific legal code,

71
00:04:43,520 --> 00:04:47,540
a certain level of agricultural technology, and a specific wealth distribution.

72
00:04:48,420 --> 00:04:53,480
All of those variables combine to place you at one single specific point in the state space.

73
00:04:53,580 --> 00:04:54,440
Okay, I follow that.

74
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:57,700
So if a massive famine hits, and half the population leaves,

75
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:01,100
our society moves to a completely different point in the state space.

76
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:01,340
Right.

77
00:05:01,400 --> 00:05:04,060
Or if we invent the steam engine, we jump to another point.

78
00:05:04,100 --> 00:05:04,360
Correct.

79
00:05:04,620 --> 00:05:10,160
State space is the entire theoretically possible universe of conditions a society could ever find itself in.

80
00:05:10,180 --> 00:05:10,800
The whole map.

81
00:05:10,800 --> 00:05:11,540
The whole map.

82
00:05:12,140 --> 00:05:17,160
But, and this is a crucial caveat, you cannot just teleport anywhere on that map.

83
00:05:17,320 --> 00:05:17,800
What do you mean?

84
00:05:18,080 --> 00:05:26,560
Well, if you are a Bronze Age tribe, you cannot suddenly jump to the space-faring civilization point in the state space.

85
00:05:26,620 --> 00:05:29,720
You have to navigate there step by step from where you currently are.

86
00:05:29,820 --> 00:05:30,420
Oh, right.

87
00:05:30,500 --> 00:05:32,000
You're constrained by reality.

88
00:05:32,180 --> 00:05:32,580
Exactly.

89
00:05:32,980 --> 00:05:36,820
Which brings us to the second concept, and I spent a lot of time shooing on this one

90
00:05:36,820 --> 00:05:41,820
because it's arguably the most important idea in the whole paper, the forward admissible cone.

91
00:05:42,120 --> 00:05:42,440
Yes.

92
00:05:42,860 --> 00:05:48,220
It's a concept borrowed from viability theory, and it is brilliant in its application here.

93
00:05:48,340 --> 00:05:49,400
Unpack it for us.

94
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:56,600
So, for any state your civilization is currently occupying, the forward admissible cone is a geometric shape.

95
00:05:57,040 --> 00:06:01,080
Literally a cone radiating outward from your current position into the future.

96
00:06:01,180 --> 00:06:02,140
Radiating forward.

97
00:06:02,380 --> 00:06:02,580
Right.

98
00:06:02,580 --> 00:06:07,500
And it represents the immediate safe directions your society can move without hitting a wall.

99
00:06:07,880 --> 00:06:11,220
And when we say wall, we aren't talking about a physical brick wall, obviously.

100
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:11,600
No, no.

101
00:06:11,640 --> 00:06:19,220
We mean an existential constraint, like an institutional collapse, a hard ecological boundary, a total economic failure.

102
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:27,500
The cone is the set of trajectories you can take that are actually practically viable without causing a collapse.

103
00:06:27,640 --> 00:06:31,980
Let me try an analogy here because I really want you, the listener, to visualize this.

104
00:06:31,980 --> 00:06:32,700
Go for it.

105
00:06:33,160 --> 00:06:37,520
Picture yourself driving a car down a very steep winding mountain path.

106
00:06:37,780 --> 00:06:38,040
Okay.

107
00:06:38,240 --> 00:06:43,220
There's a sheer cliff on your left side and a solid rock wall on your right.

108
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:50,260
The cone we are talking about is the range of angles you can safely turn your steering wheel that will keep you on the paved road.

109
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:51,060
That's a great visual.

110
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:51,540
Right.

111
00:06:51,700 --> 00:06:55,700
Because if you steer within that narrow cone, you keep driving forward into the future.

112
00:06:55,960 --> 00:06:56,140
Right.

113
00:06:56,380 --> 00:07:03,240
But if you steer outside the cone-like, if you yank the whale too hard to the left or right, you either hit the rock wall or you fly off the cliff.

114
00:07:03,340 --> 00:07:04,400
You violated a constraint.

115
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:05,160
Exactly.

116
00:07:05,440 --> 00:07:07,720
You are no longer on an admissible trajectory.

117
00:07:07,940 --> 00:07:08,400
You're dead.

118
00:07:08,400 --> 00:07:11,120
It is a highly accurate visualization.

119
00:07:11,740 --> 00:07:19,220
The paper explicitly defines an admissible trajectory as a path where your movement always stays inside that safe cone over time.

120
00:07:19,560 --> 00:07:28,720
And if you map out the total collection of all the safe places you could eventually reach by staying within the cone, step after step, generation after generation.

121
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:29,340
What's that called?

122
00:07:29,700 --> 00:07:32,620
That totality is called the admissible future manifold.

123
00:07:33,540 --> 00:07:36,220
It is the entire landscape of your reachable future.

124
00:07:36,220 --> 00:07:37,240
The entire landscape.

125
00:07:37,860 --> 00:07:40,840
But mountain roads aren't always wide, easy highways.

126
00:07:41,120 --> 00:07:41,620
No, they are not.

127
00:07:41,740 --> 00:07:43,220
Sometimes the road narrows.

128
00:07:43,560 --> 00:07:45,900
Sometimes a landslide blocks half the lane.

129
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,800
And that is where the geometry gets incredibly revealing.

130
00:07:49,340 --> 00:07:53,360
Because the paper introduces the mathematics of what happens when that road narrows.

131
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:59,560
It details Proposition 2, boundary curvature in bottleneck geometry.

132
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:00,560
Bottleneck geometry.

133
00:08:00,760 --> 00:08:04,920
I read this part like three times because the math felt so ominous to me.

134
00:08:04,920 --> 00:08:06,880
How does it actually work?

135
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:08,480
Let's stick with your mountain road.

136
00:08:08,640 --> 00:08:08,820
Okay.

137
00:08:09,040 --> 00:08:12,440
When the road is wide, your forward admissible cone is wide.

138
00:08:12,660 --> 00:08:15,200
You have a massive range of safe steering angles.

139
00:08:15,420 --> 00:08:15,540
Right.

140
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:19,820
I can drift a little to the left to look at the view, drift to the right to avoid a pothole.

141
00:08:19,920 --> 00:08:20,340
Exactly.

142
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:21,600
You have plenty of room for air.

143
00:08:22,200 --> 00:08:25,080
The steering effort required to just survive is minimal.

144
00:08:25,540 --> 00:08:32,000
But what happens when the path narrows into a tiny single lane bottleneck with a sheer drop on both sides?

145
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:33,040
The walls close in.

146
00:08:33,040 --> 00:08:34,120
The walls close in.

147
00:08:34,300 --> 00:08:35,080
The cone shrinks.

148
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:38,660
The range of safe steering angles gets terrifyingly tiny.

149
00:08:38,880 --> 00:08:39,000
Okay.

150
00:08:39,120 --> 00:08:41,100
So mathematically, what's happening there?

151
00:08:41,300 --> 00:08:48,800
Mathematically, as the angle of that safe cone approaches zero, the curvature of the boundary diverges toward infinity.

152
00:08:48,980 --> 00:08:49,500
Infinity.

153
00:08:49,760 --> 00:08:50,140
Infinity.

154
00:08:50,140 --> 00:08:56,060
In your analogy, curvature is the per se steering effort required to avoid a fatal crash.

155
00:08:56,200 --> 00:08:57,160
Oh, wow.

156
00:08:57,260 --> 00:09:03,100
When your options narrow, the sheer navigational effort required just to stay alive becomes infinitely high.

157
00:09:03,940 --> 00:09:07,240
Small, everyday mistakes suddenly become instantly fatal.

158
00:09:07,480 --> 00:09:08,140
Wait, hold on.

159
00:09:08,140 --> 00:09:14,040
I'm struggling to see how this translates from like a mathematical steering wheel to actual human leadership.

160
00:09:14,040 --> 00:09:14,940
How so?

161
00:09:15,100 --> 00:09:21,900
Well, are we saying that every historical crisis just requires a genius leader with infinite steering precision to get through it?

162
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:25,680
Because that sounds more like the great man theory of history than math.

163
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:27,460
Oh, that's a great distinction to make.

164
00:09:27,660 --> 00:09:29,980
No, the math is actually arguing the exact opposite.

165
00:09:30,060 --> 00:09:30,400
Oh, really?

166
00:09:30,660 --> 00:09:30,900
Yeah.

167
00:09:31,300 --> 00:09:38,420
It's saying that when the structural curvature diverges toward infinity, no leader is good enough to guarantee survival.

168
00:09:38,740 --> 00:09:39,160
Oh.

169
00:09:39,160 --> 00:09:42,120
The system itself becomes hyper-fragile.

170
00:09:42,280 --> 00:09:44,100
It doesn't matter if you have a genius at the wheel.

171
00:09:44,540 --> 00:09:51,180
If the safe steering angle is a fraction of a millimeter, eventually human error will send the car off the cliff.

172
00:09:51,260 --> 00:09:55,180
So it's about the structure of the situation, not the skill of the driver.

173
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:55,820
Exactly.

174
00:09:56,260 --> 00:09:59,700
Let's bring in a real-world strategic equivalent to make this concrete.

175
00:09:59,820 --> 00:10:00,200
Please.

176
00:10:00,640 --> 00:10:06,880
The paper links this mathematical curvature to a concept from the legendary Intel CEO, Andy Grove.

177
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:08,560
Oh, the inflection point.

178
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:08,880
Yes.

179
00:10:09,320 --> 00:10:12,060
He talked extensively about strategic inflection points.

180
00:10:12,820 --> 00:10:20,100
In Grove's framework, an inflection point is a moment where a business or a civilization faces a massive structural shift in its environment.

181
00:10:20,300 --> 00:10:25,880
Like when the internet was invented and suddenly every print media company realized their mountain road just disappeared.

182
00:10:26,100 --> 00:10:26,540
Exactly.

183
00:10:26,680 --> 00:10:28,980
Or a sudden permanent resource shortage.

184
00:10:29,360 --> 00:10:34,880
In the language of Fliction's paper, a strategic inflection point is a moment of extreme reachability curvature.

185
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:39,220
The safe cone has shrunk drastically due to external forces.

186
00:10:39,640 --> 00:10:40,320
The road got narrow.

187
00:10:40,700 --> 00:10:41,880
The road got extremely narrow.

188
00:10:42,380 --> 00:10:55,480
At that precise moment in time, tiny positional changes, a slight tweak in corporate strategy, a minor government policy decision, produce massive irreversible shifts in what futures remain accessible.

189
00:10:55,480 --> 00:10:57,280
Because you're right on the edge of the cliff.

190
00:10:57,280 --> 00:10:57,640
Right.

191
00:10:57,840 --> 00:11:06,340
If you don't steer with near infinite precision during that specific bottleneck, your admissible future manifold drops to zero, you go bankrupt.

192
00:11:06,520 --> 00:11:07,160
You collapse.

193
00:11:07,380 --> 00:11:09,280
Think about Intel in the 1980s.

194
00:11:09,360 --> 00:11:12,620
I mean, Japanese companies started dominating the memory chip market.

195
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:13,020
Right.

196
00:11:13,020 --> 00:11:14,820
And Intel was a memory company.

197
00:11:14,960 --> 00:11:15,960
That was their whole road.

198
00:11:16,620 --> 00:11:18,540
Suddenly, the road narrowed to zero.

199
00:11:19,180 --> 00:11:26,440
Grove and Gordon Moore had to make an agonizing, incredibly precise turn to abandon memory entirely and switch to microprocessors.

200
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:27,700
Which was a massive risk.

201
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:28,320
Huge.

202
00:11:28,720 --> 00:11:33,220
If they steered even slightly wrong or hesitated for six months, Intel would not exist today.

203
00:11:33,320 --> 00:11:34,340
That is infinite curvature.

204
00:11:34,800 --> 00:11:35,220
It is.

205
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:41,600
And very few entities survive moments of infinite curvature through sheer luck or perfect steering.

206
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:44,220
So how do you survive the tightrope walk, then?

207
00:11:44,520 --> 00:11:48,240
You build safety nets into the geometry before you get to the tightrope.

208
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:48,820
Ah.

209
00:11:49,320 --> 00:11:52,760
And that brings us to the final piece of our foundational framework.

210
00:11:53,660 --> 00:11:54,740
Repair corridors.

211
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:56,280
The safety nets.

212
00:11:56,580 --> 00:11:57,760
The emergency backups.

213
00:11:57,960 --> 00:11:58,380
Exactly.

214
00:11:59,020 --> 00:12:10,020
The paper defines a repair corridor as a specific, viable pathway that allows a system to navigate from a state of acute danger back into a safe region of the state space.

215
00:12:10,220 --> 00:12:10,560
Okay.

216
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:16,060
It's a route to recovery, where forward motion remains mathematically possible the whole time.

217
00:12:16,240 --> 00:12:17,860
You aren't just freezing in place.

218
00:12:18,220 --> 00:12:19,980
You are actively moving towards safety.

219
00:12:20,260 --> 00:12:20,420
Right.

220
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:25,480
And crucially, the paper emphasizes the need for robust repair corridors.

221
00:12:25,760 --> 00:12:29,200
What makes it robust, as opposed to just a regular repair corridor?

222
00:12:29,360 --> 00:12:33,340
A robust corridor is one that doesn't disappear just because of a slight miscalculation.

223
00:12:33,340 --> 00:12:40,520
If you get bumped slightly off course by an unpredictable shock, a robust repair corridor is wide enough that it's still there to catch you.

224
00:12:40,520 --> 00:12:40,940
Okay.

225
00:12:41,080 --> 00:12:42,600
Bringing it back to the car on the mountain.

226
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:47,360
A repair corridor is like an emergency runaway truck ramp.

227
00:12:47,700 --> 00:12:47,960
Perfect.

228
00:12:48,180 --> 00:12:48,520
Yes.

229
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:48,960
Right.

230
00:12:48,960 --> 00:12:58,740
Like if you're barreling down a steep grade and your brakes suddenly fail, which is a massive shock to your system, you have a predefined safe path you can steer into.

231
00:12:58,900 --> 00:12:59,820
The runaway ramp.

232
00:12:59,880 --> 00:13:00,360
Exactly.

233
00:13:00,720 --> 00:13:06,180
The ramp absorbs the shock, slows you down using gravel, and prevents you from flying off the cliff.

234
00:13:06,180 --> 00:13:17,400
And a robust repair corridor means the ramp is wide enough and clearly marked enough that even if your car is violently fishtailing, you can still manage to hit it.

235
00:13:17,640 --> 00:13:25,540
That visual captures the math perfectly, and this concept is vital for everything, from global supply chains to ecological conservation.

236
00:13:25,700 --> 00:13:25,900
Yeah.

237
00:13:26,120 --> 00:13:29,700
The health of a civilization isn't just about how fast it's driving down the road.

238
00:13:29,880 --> 00:13:34,680
It's about how many robust repair corridors it has proactively built into its landscape.

239
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:36,340
Right, because if you don't have them...

240
00:13:36,340 --> 00:13:41,020
A society with no runaway ramps has to drive perfectly forever, and no one drives perfectly forever.

241
00:13:41,340 --> 00:13:41,760
No one.

242
00:13:42,680 --> 00:13:54,780
Which is an incredible segue into the next massive idea here, because if building these robust repair corridors is the key to survival, how do we actually know if a society has enough of them?

243
00:13:54,960 --> 00:13:56,180
How do you measure the invisible?

244
00:13:56,340 --> 00:13:56,780
Exactly.

245
00:13:56,940 --> 00:13:57,660
How do you measure it?

246
00:13:57,660 --> 00:14:04,740
The paper argues there are two vital metrics we must track, two master variables that dictate the destiny of any complex system.

247
00:14:04,800 --> 00:14:04,960
All right.

248
00:14:05,320 --> 00:14:07,700
The first is volume, and the second is entropy.

249
00:14:08,320 --> 00:14:17,160
Specifically, weighted reachability volume, which the paper denotes algebraically as VR, and reachability entropy, denoted as HR.

250
00:14:17,160 --> 00:14:19,100
Okay, let's unpack volume first.

251
00:14:19,720 --> 00:14:20,900
Weighted reachability volume.

252
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:25,180
In layman's terms, this is just the sheer size of your accessible future, correct?

253
00:14:25,480 --> 00:14:26,220
Essentially, yes.

254
00:14:26,260 --> 00:14:28,000
It is the raw scale of possibility.

255
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:30,360
Volume measures how much future you have.

256
00:14:30,700 --> 00:14:37,280
If you look at the state space map, how many different safe conditions can your society realistically reach from where it is standing today?

257
00:14:37,560 --> 00:14:38,240
That makes sense.

258
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:40,680
But we have to pay attention to the weighted part of the term.

259
00:14:41,020 --> 00:14:44,220
The paper applies a robustness weight to these potential futures.

260
00:14:44,340 --> 00:14:46,400
Meaning not all futures are created equal.

261
00:14:46,400 --> 00:14:47,540
Far from it.

262
00:14:48,060 --> 00:15:00,520
If a specific future requires extreme painful repair costs to reach, say, you can survive a famine, but only by eating all your seed grain and sacrificing a generation.

263
00:15:00,660 --> 00:15:00,820
No.

264
00:15:01,340 --> 00:15:08,500
Or if the safe cone leading to that future is paper thin and requires infinite curvature to navigate, the math assigns it a much lower weight.

265
00:15:08,660 --> 00:15:10,260
Because it's barely a viable option.

266
00:15:10,340 --> 00:15:10,820
Exactly.

267
00:15:10,820 --> 00:15:15,360
So VR isn't just a naive, raw count of every theoretical possibility.

268
00:15:15,880 --> 00:15:23,380
It's a realistic measure of the rich, accessible, realistically survivable futures you have at your disposal.

269
00:15:23,600 --> 00:15:23,760
Okay.

270
00:15:23,880 --> 00:15:25,020
So high volume is good.

271
00:15:25,240 --> 00:15:30,500
We want a big, wide open future with lots of heavily weighted, easy to reach safe states.

272
00:15:30,740 --> 00:15:30,920
Yeah.

273
00:15:30,920 --> 00:15:37,200
But here is where the paper absolutely blew my mind and why I think everyone listening needs to pay really close attention to this next point.

274
00:15:37,780 --> 00:15:39,580
Volume alone is not enough.

275
00:15:39,760 --> 00:15:39,900
No.

276
00:15:40,200 --> 00:15:43,060
In fact, optimizing only for volume might kill you.

277
00:15:43,340 --> 00:15:44,320
You also need entropy.

278
00:15:44,320 --> 00:15:46,860
And the author makes a brilliant intellectual leap here.

279
00:15:47,080 --> 00:15:51,980
They import Shannon entropy, which is a concept originally from information theory and thermodynamics.

280
00:15:52,180 --> 00:15:52,360
Right.

281
00:15:52,420 --> 00:15:54,420
And they apply it to civilizational futures.

282
00:15:55,600 --> 00:15:58,920
Reachability entropy doesn't measure how many futures there are.

283
00:15:59,160 --> 00:16:02,920
It measures how qualitatively distinct those futures are from one another.

284
00:16:03,100 --> 00:16:05,200
This is the absolute crux of the issue.

285
00:16:05,440 --> 00:16:09,540
Let me translate this directly to you, the listener, maybe thinking about your career or your investments.

286
00:16:09,900 --> 00:16:10,160
Okay.

287
00:16:10,160 --> 00:16:15,220
Having high volume is like having a hundred different job offers sitting on your desk.

288
00:16:15,340 --> 00:16:16,060
Sounds great.

289
00:16:16,200 --> 00:16:16,420
Right.

290
00:16:16,520 --> 00:16:17,740
You feel incredibly secure.

291
00:16:17,940 --> 00:16:19,380
You have a hundred paths forward.

292
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:20,780
Your VR is massive.

293
00:16:21,260 --> 00:16:21,400
Right.

294
00:16:21,840 --> 00:16:30,880
But what if all 100 of those job offers are for the exact same position in the exact same fragile industry?

295
00:16:31,300 --> 00:16:35,740
Say it's 1999 and you have a hundred lucrative offers to be a fax machine salesman.

296
00:16:35,820 --> 00:16:39,700
Well, your volume is historically high, but your entropy is strictly zero.

297
00:16:39,700 --> 00:16:40,100
Yes.

298
00:16:40,640 --> 00:16:49,100
Because if that one specific industry crashes like, if email suddenly becomes ubiquitous, all 100 of your options vanish simultaneously.

299
00:16:49,400 --> 00:16:49,840
Instantly.

300
00:16:50,120 --> 00:16:53,220
The sheer number of offers didn't protect you at all because they weren't distinct.

301
00:16:53,640 --> 00:16:58,080
High entropy, on the other hand, means having options in completely different, unconnected fields.

302
00:16:58,540 --> 00:16:58,760
Right.

303
00:16:58,920 --> 00:17:02,000
You have an offer in tech, an offer in agriculture, an offer in teaching.

304
00:17:02,200 --> 00:17:04,220
They are qualitatively distinct pathways.

305
00:17:04,460 --> 00:17:04,820
Exactly.

306
00:17:04,820 --> 00:17:09,400
What's fascinating here is how the paper formalizes this in definition six.

307
00:17:10,080 --> 00:17:16,820
It states that entropy is calculated over a macroscopic partition of qualitatively distinct future types.

308
00:17:17,220 --> 00:17:19,260
Break that down for a nation state.

309
00:17:19,380 --> 00:17:19,600
Sure.

310
00:17:19,780 --> 00:17:21,040
Let's apply this to a nation state.

311
00:17:21,260 --> 00:17:25,520
Different institutional regimes, different technological pathways, different energy sources.

312
00:17:25,520 --> 00:17:37,160
If your society's entire economic future is concentrated into a single type, say, exporting a single natural resource like oil, your entropy is incredibly low.

313
00:17:37,420 --> 00:17:37,620
Yeah.

314
00:17:37,880 --> 00:17:39,880
Even if your bank accounts are currently full.

315
00:17:40,060 --> 00:17:41,580
Even if your volume is huge.

316
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:41,840
Right.

317
00:17:41,840 --> 00:17:48,020
But if your futures are spread across advanced manufacturing, software, agriculture, and renewable energy, your entropy is high.

318
00:17:48,640 --> 00:17:50,100
Let me play devil's advocate here.

319
00:17:50,200 --> 00:17:50,380
Sure.

320
00:17:50,760 --> 00:17:55,400
Why do we humans always seem to sacrifice entropy for volume?

321
00:17:55,840 --> 00:18:02,200
Because it feels like every corporation, every government naturally gravitates toward becoming the fax machine salesman.

322
00:18:02,420 --> 00:18:03,500
That's a great question.

323
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:06,960
Because volume is easily measurable.

324
00:18:07,480 --> 00:18:11,000
And it usually correlates with short-term efficiency and wealth.

325
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:17,980
If you dedicate all your farmland to a single, hyper-yielding crop, your volume goes through the roof.

326
00:18:18,240 --> 00:18:20,100
Your quarterly earnings look amazing.

327
00:18:20,220 --> 00:18:21,740
You look like a genius on paper.

328
00:18:21,940 --> 00:18:22,320
Exactly.

329
00:18:23,240 --> 00:18:26,920
Entropy, on the other hand, requires deliberate inefficiency.

330
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:28,540
Deliberate inefficiency.

331
00:18:28,820 --> 00:18:28,960
Right.

332
00:18:29,200 --> 00:18:33,920
It means planting crops that might not yield as much cash today just to ensure genetic diversity.

333
00:18:34,480 --> 00:18:36,640
Entropy is an invisible safety net.

334
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,380
You only realize its value the moment you need it.

335
00:18:39,380 --> 00:18:43,660
The classic example is the Irish potato famine in the 1840s.

336
00:18:43,740 --> 00:18:45,220
A tragic but perfect example.

337
00:18:45,440 --> 00:18:52,000
They maximized volume by planting the lumper potato because it grew incredibly well in poor soil and fed millions.

338
00:18:52,120 --> 00:18:52,360
Right.

339
00:18:52,360 --> 00:18:57,120
The volume was off the charts, but the entropy was practically zero because it was a monoculture.

340
00:18:57,740 --> 00:19:00,900
Every single potato was essentially a genetic clone of the others.

341
00:19:01,100 --> 00:19:02,160
Directly zero entropy.

342
00:19:02,160 --> 00:19:07,740
So when the Phytothora and Festin's blight arrived, it didn't just kill some potatoes, it killed all of them.

343
00:19:07,980 --> 00:19:11,300
The entire admissible future manifold collapsed overnight.

344
00:19:11,600 --> 00:19:13,920
Because there were no distinct repair corridors.

345
00:19:14,560 --> 00:19:16,500
There was no alternative crop infrastructure.

346
00:19:16,860 --> 00:19:19,960
That historical tragedy perfectly maps onto the math.

347
00:19:20,520 --> 00:19:26,120
A repair corridor is entirely useless if it relies on the exact same mechanism that just failed.

348
00:19:26,120 --> 00:19:26,800
Obviously.

349
00:19:27,240 --> 00:19:32,300
If your potato fails, your backup plan can't be plant more of the same potato.

350
00:19:32,420 --> 00:19:32,820
Exactly.

351
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:34,220
You don't have a backup plan.

352
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:48,160
But if you have high entropy, if you have distinct pathways involving maritime trade or alternative grain agriculture or a robust industrial sector you can pivot to, you have independent repair corridors.

353
00:19:48,500 --> 00:19:50,020
You can navigate around the constraint.

354
00:19:50,200 --> 00:19:50,700
You survive.

355
00:19:50,700 --> 00:19:58,620
So to summarize, volume is the sheer size of your safety net, but entropy is the diversity of the materials that nut is made of.

356
00:19:58,680 --> 00:19:59,240
I like that.

357
00:19:59,340 --> 00:20:06,400
If the net is huge, stretching for miles, but it's made entirely of a material that dissolves in water, the moment it starts raining, you're dead.

358
00:20:06,620 --> 00:20:09,240
It's a visceral way to put it, but it's mathematically sound.

359
00:20:09,400 --> 00:20:13,240
And the author leaves us with a profound thought on this in the paper's remark one.

360
00:20:13,240 --> 00:20:19,080
They state that the deepest, most fundamental truth of a civilization isn't a number on a shred sheet.

361
00:20:19,600 --> 00:20:25,340
It is the actual topology, the multidimensional geometric shape of its future space.

362
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:26,580
The shape of the future.

363
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:26,960
Right.

364
00:20:27,280 --> 00:20:31,200
Volume and entropy are just our best human attempts to measure that shape.

365
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:37,320
They are scalar approximations, shadows on the cave wall of a massive hidden reality.

366
00:20:37,320 --> 00:20:37,700
Okay.

367
00:20:37,820 --> 00:20:38,980
We have our structural framework.

368
00:20:39,240 --> 00:20:43,500
We understand state space, cones, repair corridors, volume, and entropy.

369
00:20:43,680 --> 00:20:44,280
We have the tools.

370
00:20:44,620 --> 00:20:48,560
Now, the paper takes this mathematical lens and does something wild.

371
00:20:48,680 --> 00:20:50,680
It applies it to the entirety of human history.

372
00:20:50,760 --> 00:20:51,220
It does.

373
00:20:51,320 --> 00:20:58,340
So let's travel back to the dawn of civilization, unpacking the first of our three core books, Peter Turchin's Ultra Society.

374
00:20:58,760 --> 00:21:00,620
Ultra Society is a monumental work.

375
00:21:01,060 --> 00:21:05,040
It looks at the evolution of large-scale cooperation over the last 10,000 years.

376
00:21:05,120 --> 00:21:05,400
Right.

377
00:21:05,400 --> 00:21:15,260
How did humanity transition from roaming in small bands of a few dozen hunter-gatherers to building massive, globally interconnected civilizations of billions?

378
00:21:15,540 --> 00:21:16,660
It's a huge leap.

379
00:21:16,820 --> 00:21:17,240
It is.

380
00:21:17,620 --> 00:21:23,200
And the conventional sociological and biological reading relies heavily on cultural group selection.

381
00:21:23,480 --> 00:21:24,820
Which means what, exactly?

382
00:21:25,400 --> 00:21:31,640
The idea is that groups of humans that develop strong cultural mechanisms to suppress selfish defection meaning,

383
00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:37,120
they learn to cooperate and punish cheaters out-competed groups that couldn't cooperate.

384
00:21:37,320 --> 00:21:37,520
Right.

385
00:21:37,640 --> 00:21:40,140
The classic united we stand, divided we fall.

386
00:21:40,420 --> 00:21:42,600
The cooperative tribe survives the winter.

387
00:21:43,060 --> 00:21:44,840
The selfish tribe starves.

388
00:21:45,060 --> 00:21:45,460
Exactly.

389
00:21:46,060 --> 00:21:49,700
But Fliction's paper flips that conventional perspective on its head.

390
00:21:50,120 --> 00:21:50,420
Okay.

391
00:21:50,680 --> 00:21:51,060
How so?

392
00:21:51,220 --> 00:21:54,240
It reframes the biological imperative as a geometric one.

393
00:21:54,240 --> 00:22:03,120
The paper argues that what intergroup competition was actually selecting for wasn't just cooperation as some abstract moral good.

394
00:22:03,800 --> 00:22:10,820
Evolution was physically selecting for societies that possessed larger reachability volume and higher reachability entropy.

395
00:22:11,220 --> 00:22:11,560
Wow.

396
00:22:12,100 --> 00:22:13,700
The math drove the evolution.

397
00:22:14,020 --> 00:22:14,280
Yes.

398
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:17,200
Cooperation is merely the proximate social mechanism.

399
00:22:17,900 --> 00:22:21,180
Expanded geometric future volume is the ultimate selected quantity.

400
00:22:21,180 --> 00:22:25,600
There's a memorable quote from the source text that just hit me like a ton of bricks when I read it.

401
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:26,040
Which one?

402
00:22:26,340 --> 00:22:27,160
The paper says,

403
00:22:27,600 --> 00:22:29,180
A band cannot build a telescope.

404
00:22:29,560 --> 00:22:30,740
A civilization can.

405
00:22:31,100 --> 00:22:33,700
It's a beautiful distillation of the entire concept.

406
00:22:34,040 --> 00:22:35,640
Let's unpack why that is.

407
00:22:36,100 --> 00:22:38,620
Why can't a band build a telescope?

408
00:22:39,220 --> 00:22:43,940
Think deeply about the state space required to reach the build a telescope point.

409
00:22:44,060 --> 00:22:44,280
Yeah.

410
00:22:44,720 --> 00:22:47,440
You need advanced mining techniques to get the ore.

411
00:22:47,820 --> 00:22:50,360
You need metallurgy to forge the brass.

412
00:22:50,360 --> 00:22:54,000
You need a deep understanding of optics and glassblowing.

413
00:22:54,520 --> 00:22:57,120
You need advanced calculus and geometry.

414
00:22:57,600 --> 00:22:59,060
You need a lot of distinct pathways.

415
00:22:59,320 --> 00:23:08,200
And you need a massive, stable surplus of food to feed the scientists and artisans who are spending all day grinding lenses instead of hunting.

416
00:23:08,620 --> 00:23:13,180
You need a stable legal system to protect the property and the knowledge over generations.

417
00:23:13,480 --> 00:23:13,680
Right.

418
00:23:13,760 --> 00:23:16,400
Because otherwise someone just steals the brass to make a spear.

419
00:23:16,400 --> 00:23:17,080
Exactly.

420
00:23:17,760 --> 00:23:22,020
A small band of 50 people, no matter how intelligent or morally cooperative they are,

421
00:23:22,460 --> 00:23:27,940
simply does not possess a wide enough forward admissible cone to ever reach the telescope state.

422
00:23:28,200 --> 00:23:30,340
The physics of their reality won't allow it.

423
00:23:30,340 --> 00:23:31,620
They literally don't have the volume.

424
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:35,820
But when that tribe figures out how to scale up into a civilization of millions,

425
00:23:36,220 --> 00:23:37,840
they unlock the division of labor.

426
00:23:37,840 --> 00:23:43,880
One person farms, a thousand people mine, ten people grind lenses, and one person writes the math.

427
00:23:44,560 --> 00:23:50,580
And by doing so, as the paper states, they physically expand the collective admissible manifold.

428
00:23:50,760 --> 00:23:51,680
It's amazing.

429
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:57,580
The paper also explicitly mentions the evolutionary role of reverse dominance hierarchies.

430
00:23:57,780 --> 00:23:58,760
I saw that.

431
00:23:58,880 --> 00:23:59,520
What are those?

432
00:23:59,640 --> 00:24:08,460
These are cultural systems where the group actively prevents a single tyrant or an alpha male from monopolizing all the resources and decision-making power.

433
00:24:08,460 --> 00:24:13,920
Wait, so democracy, or at least the distribution of power, isn't just a moral triumph of the Enlightenment.

434
00:24:14,060 --> 00:24:15,980
It's a mathematical hack for survival.

435
00:24:16,360 --> 00:24:18,320
That is exactly what the geometry implies.

436
00:24:18,320 --> 00:24:26,500
By distributing access to the future across the group, rather than concentrating all the reachability volume into the narrow whims of a single dictator,

437
00:24:26,960 --> 00:24:30,900
the society as a whole unlocks vastly more distinct pathways.

438
00:24:31,220 --> 00:24:32,220
Which means more entropy.

439
00:24:32,720 --> 00:24:33,200
Exactly.

440
00:24:33,440 --> 00:24:35,560
A dictator might only fund the military.

441
00:24:36,240 --> 00:24:39,840
A distributed society funds the military, the arts, agriculture, and science.

442
00:24:40,180 --> 00:24:41,920
They drastically increase their entropy.

443
00:24:42,160 --> 00:24:44,240
But okay, this introduces a massive paradox.

444
00:24:44,520 --> 00:24:44,860
What is it?

445
00:24:44,860 --> 00:24:56,520
How does a society explore all these new, crazy technological and social pathways without accidentally destroying the very cooperation that got them there in the first place?

446
00:24:56,680 --> 00:24:56,960
Right.

447
00:24:56,960 --> 00:25:02,800
I mean, if you let people experiment with new ideas, some of those ideas might be, let's overthrow the government.

448
00:25:03,400 --> 00:25:11,220
How do you invent the printing press, which fundamentally disrupts power, or the steam engine without shattering your social order and falling off the cliff?

449
00:25:11,220 --> 00:25:16,920
This is where the paper weaves in biology again, specifically referencing the neutral network theorem.

450
00:25:17,160 --> 00:25:18,180
I found this fascinating.

451
00:25:18,600 --> 00:25:23,000
Explain how biological neutral networks map onto human societies.

452
00:25:23,500 --> 00:25:26,680
The concept originates with evolutionary biologist Andreas Wagner.

453
00:25:27,720 --> 00:25:36,280
In genetics, a neutral network is a vast, interconnected web of genetic mutations that an organism can undergo without altering its core, vital functions.

454
00:25:36,280 --> 00:25:39,000
Okay, so it can change, but it doesn't die.

455
00:25:39,120 --> 00:25:39,300
Right.

456
00:25:39,620 --> 00:25:41,020
It can change its internal code.

457
00:25:41,220 --> 00:25:44,880
It can drift around genetically, trying out millions of microscopic variations.

458
00:25:45,160 --> 00:25:49,160
But the organism still survives and functions just fine in its current environment.

459
00:25:49,580 --> 00:25:53,880
It isn't punished by natural selection for exploring these neutral states.

460
00:25:54,200 --> 00:25:56,360
It's exploring the state space safely.

461
00:25:56,560 --> 00:25:56,900
Exactly.

462
00:25:57,020 --> 00:26:00,180
It's kind of like a jazz musician improvising over a bass line.

463
00:26:00,680 --> 00:26:04,820
As long as they stay in key, the song doesn't collapse, even if they hit some weird notes.

464
00:26:04,820 --> 00:26:06,140
That's a great way to think about it.

465
00:26:06,540 --> 00:26:11,580
The paper's Proposition 4 applies this biological reality to human civilizations.

466
00:26:11,920 --> 00:26:12,220
Okay.

467
00:26:12,580 --> 00:26:20,820
A civilization with a large, robust, neutral network of safe, cooperative states has a massive frontier.

468
00:26:21,260 --> 00:26:22,760
It has a massive playground.

469
00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:24,600
It can experiment wildly.

470
00:26:24,860 --> 00:26:25,640
Try new things.

471
00:26:25,740 --> 00:26:27,280
It can try a new monetary policy.

472
00:26:27,500 --> 00:26:29,700
It can invent a new philosophical movement.

473
00:26:29,700 --> 00:26:32,080
It can restructure its local markets.

474
00:26:32,680 --> 00:26:36,640
Because of the core cooperative function, the bass line, is deeply preserved.

475
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:42,960
The society can probe into the unknown without stepping outside its safe, admissible cone.

476
00:26:43,100 --> 00:26:44,640
So let's look at the inverse of that.

477
00:26:44,700 --> 00:26:44,900
Okay.

478
00:26:45,020 --> 00:26:50,440
A hyper-rigid, traditional society that violently punishes any deviation from the norm-like,

479
00:26:50,840 --> 00:26:55,000
a society that arrests anyone who suggests a new way of farming or a new way of governing,

480
00:26:55,420 --> 00:26:58,320
has an infinitesimally small, neutral network.

481
00:26:58,420 --> 00:26:58,820
Very small.

482
00:26:58,820 --> 00:27:00,320
It can't explore.

483
00:27:00,480 --> 00:27:01,320
It stagnates.

484
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:07,520
But a society that tolerates harmless deviance, that actively allows for safe experimentation,

485
00:27:07,940 --> 00:27:09,640
builds this massive frontier.

